# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-aurora-theater-shooting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The gauge of a shotgun is a list that includes all necessary data to define a functional barrel.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The concept of using a material property to define a bore diameter was used before the term "gauge" in the late 16th century.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The term *gauge* in connection of firearms was first used in the book *A Light to the Art of Gunnery* (1677).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Gauge was determined from the weight of a solid sphere of lead that would fit the bore of the firearm and is expressed as the multiplicative inverse of the sphere's mass as a fraction of a pound, e.g., a 1⁄12 lb (38 g) lead ball fits a 12-gauge bore.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Therefore, with a 12-gauge, it would take 12 balls of lead of the same size as the 12-gauge shotgun's inner bore diameter to mass 1 pound (453.6 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The term is related to the measurement of cannons, which were also measured by the weight of their iron round shot; an eight-pounder would fire an 8-pound (3.6 kg) ball.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Therefore, a 12-gauge is larger than a 16-gauge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Due to problems defining a pound and getting pure lead, the Gun Barrel Proof Act of 1855 defined a gauge as a list of defined values.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] As a result, the formula above only works as a heuristic for determining bore diameter from gauge, as the table in the law lists diameters not consistent with any possible density, even after accounting for rounding errors inherent in the table only being precise to a thousandth of an inch.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] These very large and heavy rifles, called "elephant guns", were intended primarily for use in regions of Africa and Asia to hunt large, dangerous game animals.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Gauge is commonly abbreviated as "ga.", "ga", or "G".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The British law that defined the relationship between bore diameter and gauge listed every gauge from 1 to 50.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The list here does the same: the number in the list is the gauge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The value to its right is the diameter in inches, as specified in the law.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] For convenience, the equivalent value in millimetres is provided, but this is not specified in the law.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Since shotguns were not originally intended to fire solid projectiles, but rather a compressible mass of shot, the actual diameter of the bore can vary.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The fact that most shotgun bores are not cylindrical also causes deviations from the ideal bore diameter.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The chamber of the gun is larger to accommodate the thickness of the shotshell walls, and a "forcing cone" in front of the chamber reduces the diameter down to the bore diameter.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The forcing cone can be as short as a fraction of an inch, or as long as a few inches on some firearms.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] At the muzzle end of the barrel, the choke can constrict the bore even further, so measuring the bore diameter of a shotgun is not a simple process, as it must be done away from either end.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Shotgun bores are commonly "overbored" or "backbored", meaning that most of the bore (from the forcing cone to the choke) is slightly larger than the value given by the formula.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] This is claimed to reduce felt recoil and improve patterning.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The recoil reduction is due to the larger bore producing a slower acceleration of the shot, and the patterning improvements are due to the larger muzzle diameter for the same choke constriction, which results in less shot deformation.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] A 12-gauge shotgun, nominally 18.5 mm (0.73 in), can range from a tight 18 mm (0.71 in) to an extreme overbore of 20 mm (0.79 in).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Some also claim an increased velocity with the overbored barrels, up to 15 m/s (49 ft/s), which is due to the larger swept volume of the overbored barrel.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Once only found in expensive custom shotguns, overbored barrels are now becoming common in mass-marketed guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Aftermarket backboring is also commonly performed to reduce barrel weight and shift the center of mass backward for better balance.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Factory overbored barrels generally have a larger outside diameter and will not have this weight reduction, though they are tougher because they have a normal barrel wall thickness.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Firing slugs from overbored barrels can result in very inconsistent accuracy, as the slug may be incapable of obturating to fill the oversized bore.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Shotgun gauges still in modern production include, in descending order of size, 10 gauge, 12 gauge, 16 gauge, 20 gauge, 24 gauge, 28 gauge, 32 gauge (sometimes called 14 millimeter or 32 bore), and .410 bore.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] By far, the most popular is the 12 gauge, followed by 20 gauge, particularly in the United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Shotguns and shells exceeding 10 gauge, such as the 8 gauge, 7 gauge, 6 gauge, 4 gauge, 3 gauge and 2 gauge, are historically important in the United Kingdom and elsewhere in mainland Europe.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Today, they are almost exclusively made by custom order or handloaders.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] These shells are usually black powder paper or brass cartridges, as opposed to modern smokeless powder plastic or wax cartridges.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The 18-, 15-, 11-, 6-, 3-, and 2-gauge shells are the rarest of all; owners of these types of rare shotguns will usually have their ammunition custom-loaded by a specialist in rare and custom bores.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The 14 gauge has not been loaded in the United States since the early 20th century, although the 2+9⁄16-inch (65 mm) hull is still made in France.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The smaller 24 and 32 gauges are still produced and used in some European and South American countries and are commonly available for purchase via most online ammunition vendors in the United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Punt guns, which use very large shells, are rarely encountered.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Also seen in limited numbers are smoothbore firearms in calibers smaller than .360, such as .22 long rifle (UK No.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] 3 bore), designed for short-range pest control and garden guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] All three of these rimfires are available in shot and BB-cap.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The 10 gauge narrowly escaped obsolescence when steel and other nontoxic shot became required for waterfowl hunting, since the larger shell could hold the much larger sizes of low-density steel shot needed to reach the ranges necessary for waterfowl hunting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] The move to steel shot reduced the use of 16- and 20-gauge shells for waterfowl hunting, and the shorter, 2+3⁄4-inch (70 mm), 12-gauge shells as well.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/12-gauge] Newer nontoxic shots, such as bismuth or tungsten-nickel-iron alloys, and even tungsten-polymer blends, regain much or all of the performance loss, but are much more expensive than steel or lead shot.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The **1982 Wilkes-Barre shootings** was a spree shooting which occurred in the United States on September 25, 1982, carried out by **George Emil Banks**, a former Camp Hill prison guard.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks fatally shot 13 people in Wilkes-Barre and Jenkins Township, Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The victims included seven children – five being his own – their mothers, their relatives, and one bystander.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks' attorneys argued for the insanity defense, but following a trial, Banks was convicted of 12 counts of first-degree murder and sentenced to death.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 29, 1990, the Pennsylvania State Legislature barred further use of the electric chair amid debate that electrocution was cruel and unusual punishment; it approved execution by lethal injection.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks's case was appealed and, on December 2, 2004, he received a stay of execution following a determination that he was incompetent for execution.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On May 12, 2010, Banks was declared incompetent to be executed, following a competency hearing held the previous month.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 2, 2025, Banks died in prison at the age of 83.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The shooting remains the deadliest in the history of Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On the night of September 24, 1982, Banks drank a large quantity of gin and took prescription drugs at his home on Schoolhouse Lane in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The next morning on September 25, 1982, he used an AR-15 semi-automatic rifle to kill eight people in his house, including three women in their 20s (all girlfriends and mothers of his children) and five children, four of them his.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks dressed in military fatigues and went outside, where he saw 22-year-old Jimmy Olsen and 24-year-old Ray Hall Jr, leaving a house across the street.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He shot them both, reportedly yelling that they "would not tell anyone about this" before firing.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He hit both men, fatally wounding Hall; Olsen survived.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks went to Heather Highlands mobile home park, where his former girlfriend Sharon Mazzillo and their son Kissamayu lived, of whom he had been trying to gain custody.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks forced his way in and shot Mazzillo.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He then shot and killed his sleeping son.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks killed Sharon's mother, who was trying to call the police, and Sharon's 7-year-old nephew, who was also in the home.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Sharon was shot in the heart and the other three were shot in the head.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Sharon's brothers, whom Banks did not see, hid, one in a closet and one under his mother's bed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They called the police and identified Banks as the shooter.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] When police examined the victims at the mobile home park, they connected the incident to Olsen and Hall's shooting, which had been discovered at Schoolhouse Lane.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They next found Banks's victims in his house.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Police began to search for Banks, who abandoned his car and carjacked another vehicle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After abandoning the stolen vehicle, Banks stopped in an isolated grassy area to rest, and subsequently fell asleep.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After Banks awoke, he visited his mother's house (also in Wilkes-Barre.) He was said to have confessed his crimes to her.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] She drove him to the house of Jacob Whitt, a friend of Banks, where he sent her away and prepared for a standoff with police.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] A standoff between Banks and police began.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The police brought his mother to their base to talk with Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] They tried various tactics to get the murderer to surrender, including having a false news report played over WILK radio saying that the children were alive and needed blood to survive.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The police tried other tactics to draw Banks out of the house.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Finally, Robert Brunson, a former co-worker of Banks, was able to talk him out after a 4-hour standoff.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On September 30, 1982, Banks was charged with eight counts of murder, attempted murder, aggravated assault, reckless endangerment, grand theft auto, armed robbery, and felonious theft.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Montanzima Banks (6) - Daughter of Clemens and Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Susan Yuhas (23) - Girlfriend of Banks, sister of Regina Clemens.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Boende Banks (4) - Son of Yuhas and Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Mauritania Banks (20 months) - Daughter of Yuhas and Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Dorothy Lyons (29) - Girlfriend of George Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Nancy Lyons (11) - Daughter of Dorothy Lyons.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Foraroude Banks (1) - Son of Dorothy Lyons and George Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] (24) - Bystander shot across from Banks' house on Schoolhouse Lane.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Kissmayu Banks (5) - Son of Sharon Mazzillo and George Banks.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Scott Mazzillo (7) - Nephew of Sharon Mazzillo.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Alice Mazzillo (47) - Sharon Mazzillo's mother.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 1961 at 19, after being discharged from the Army, Banks and some accomplices robbed a tavern, shooting and injuring the unarmed owner.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was sentenced to six to fifteen years in prison, which was extended when he briefly escaped in 1964; however, he was granted parole in 1969, and his sentence was commuted by then Governor Milton Shapp in 1974.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] After his release from prison, he married a black woman, Doris M.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The couple divorced in 1976, after which Banks exclusively dated white women.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] By September 1982, he had broken up with girlfriend Sharon Mazillo, who had lived with him at one time, and they were disputing custody of their young son.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was living together with three girlfriends and their four children he had fathered; one also had another man's daughter living with them.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks was hired as a correctional officer at Camp Hill, Pennsylvania, in 1980, despite his criminal record that included the eight years served in prison after the 1961 armed robbery.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 1982, shortly before his murder spree, Banks told coworkers that he believed a race war was imminent and that he wished to save the five children he had fathered with four different white girlfriends from the horrors of racism he had supposedly suffered as a child.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On September 6, he locked himself in a guard tower with a shotgun and threatened to commit suicide—as a result, he was placed on extended leave and ordered to undergo mental-health examination at a Harrisburg-area hospital.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On June 6, 1983, Banks' trial began at the Luzerne County Courthouse in Wilkes Barre, Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Albert Joseph Flora Jr. was appointed to be his defense attorney.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He said that he had only wounded some of the victims and police had killed them.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Several scene witnesses, Banks family members, and Olsen testified.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Olsen identified Banks as the person who shot him and left him for dead.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Closing arguments took place on June 21, 1983.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks' attorney argued that he was insane, but the jury found Banks guilty of 12 counts of first-degree murder, one count of third-degree murder, attempted murder, aggravated assault, and one count each of robbery, theft, and endangering the life of another person.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On June 22, 1983, the jury recommended the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Banks was incarcerated in the maximum-security unit at Huntingdon until November 1985.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Supreme Court, but it refused to overturn his verdict.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was then sent to the Correctional Institute at Graterford, where he was housed in a contained housing unit.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] From 1987 to 2000, Banks' attorneys continued to appeal his case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Supreme Court refused to hear his attorneys' argument that he lacked the mental competency to be executed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge twice signed a death warrant for Banks; however, both times federal appellate courts stayed his execution.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2001, 2006, and 2008, the court held hearings about the mental state of Banks to determine if he could be executed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He exhibited delusional behavior that caused the court to rule him incompetent for execution.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] During this period, various appeals were being heard by state and federal courts.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2010, another hearing was held on his competency; his attorney said his mental state had deteriorated significantly since 1982.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] A judge ruled that Banks was mentally incompetent for execution or to assist his attorneys in seeking clemency.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He would continue to be held in a restricted housing unit at Graterford Prison.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In September 2017, he was still on death row in Pennsylvania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was later transferred to SCI-Phoenix in May 2018.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] On November 2, 2025, Banks died at the age of 83 in his cell at SCI-Phoenix.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] The coroner said in a statement that an autopsy was performed, and the cause of death was kidney cancer.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] During appeals of his case, Banks was examined more than once in competency hearings by the court to determine if he was competent for execution.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was found mentally incompetent on three occasions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In 2006, psychiatrists testified that he was "psychotic, delusional, and irrational." In May 2010, a Luzerne County Common Pleas judge held a new hearing and determined that Banks was mentally incompetent for execution or to assist his attorney in a clemency appeal.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] In September 2017, he was held in a restricted housing unit at Graterford prison.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1982-wilkes-barre-shootings] He was relocated to SCI Phoenix following the 2018 closure of SCI Graterford.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The **Palm Sunday massacre** was a mass shooting which took place on April 15, 1984, in Brooklyn, New York, United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] It resulted in the deaths of ten people: two women, two teenage girls, and six children.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] All of the victims were shot, with a total of 19 bullets fired from two handguns at close range, most in the head, and were found in relaxed poses sitting in couches and chairs, suggesting that they had been taken by surprise.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] There were no signs of drugs or robbery at the home.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In 1985, Christopher Thomas was convicted on ten counts of manslaughter, but was cleared of murder charges.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The jury had convicted him of intentional murder, but the charges were reduced due to "extreme emotional disturbance" and Thomas being high on drugs.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Prosecutors said the motive was jealousy, claiming Thomas suspected his wife of having an affair with the home's owner, a convicted cocaine dealer named Enrique Bermudez.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Thomas's wife testified her husband was "enraged" over finding her at the Bermudez residence without him and set fire to his and her shared residence when she told him she was leaving him.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Bermudez claimed Thomas had once asked Bermudez to have sex with Thomas's wife, but Bermudez declined.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Other witnesses testified they had seen Thomas “looking bizarre” in or near the residence earlier on the day of the murders.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Bermudez confirmed this, saying Thomas had visited him that morning asking for drugs and cash.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] When Bermudez asked about some $9,000 Thomas already owed him, Thomas reportedly promised a surprise.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Thomas was sentenced to from 83 to 250 years, but due to state law was expected to spend no more than 50 years in prison.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] He ended up serving just over 32 years before being released in 2018, having served two thirds of the maximum fifty years allowed by New York State.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The sole survivor, an infant girl, was raised by her grandmother.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] Joanne Jaffe, at the time a "beat cop" and by 2014 the highest ranking female officer in the New York City Police Department, was assigned to the infant girl, and stayed in contact with her as she grew up.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] The girl lived with Jaffe starting at age 14.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In 2014, after the death of the girl's grandmother, Jaffe adopted her at the age of 31.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1984-palm-sunday-massacre] In January 2018, Thomas was paroled from prison, after being incarcerated for nearly 34 years.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On December 14, 1993, four employees were shot and killed, and a fifth employee was critically injured at a Chuck E.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Cheese's (formerly a ShowBiz Pizza Place) restaurant in Aurora, Colorado, United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] The perpetrator, 19-year-old Nathan Dunlap, a former employee of the restaurant, was frustrated about being fired five months prior to the shooting and sought revenge by committing the attack.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He fled the scene of the shooting with stolen money and restaurant items.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Cheese massacre was the deadliest mass shooting in Colorado, before being surpassed by the Columbine High School massacre in 1999.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap was found guilty of four counts of first-degree murder, attempted murder, and other charges, and was sentenced to death by lethal injection on May 17, 1996.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] A judge initially set an execution date for him in August 2013, but Colorado Governor John Hickenlooper signed a temporary reprieve that postponed Dunlap's execution date.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap's death sentence was commuted to life in prison without parole in 2020 after Colorado abolished the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Nathan Dunlap arrived at his friends' house at around 11 AM, with a .25-caliber semiautomatic pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He tells his friends he is "Going to the Chuck E.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Nathan Dunlap entered the restaurant at 9:30 p.m., where he ordered a ham and cheese sandwich and played an arcade game.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He then hid in a restroom at about 9:50 p.m.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He exited the restroom after closing at 10:05 p.m. and shot five employees with the same .25-caliber semiautomatic pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap first shot Sylvia Crowell, 19, who was cleaning the salad bar, from close range near the right ear.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Ben Grant, 17, was fatally shot near the left eye as he was vacuuming.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap then forced Colleen O'Connor, 17, who was doing closing duties in the dining room, onto her knees and fatally shot her once through the top of her head as she pleaded for her life.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Bobby Stephens, 20, the lone survivor of the shooting, returned to the restaurant after taking a smoke break outside, thinking the noise he heard from inside the restaurant were children popping balloons nearby.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] As Stephens walked into the kitchen and unloaded utensils into the dishwasher, Dunlap barged through the kitchen doors, raised the handgun at him, and fired a shot that struck Stephens in the jaw.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Stephens fell to the floor and crawled away to the exit after Dunlap walked away.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap then forced Marge Kohlberg, 50, the store manager, to unlock the safe.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] After she opened it, Dunlap shot her in the ear.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] As he was taking the cash out of the safe, Dunlap fired a second fatal shot through Kohlberg's other ear after he noticed she was still moving.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] The manager who fired Dunlap was not present at the restaurant.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Six spent shell casings were found inside the restaurant.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Stephens escaped through a back door and walked to the nearby Mill Pond apartment complex, where he pounded on a door to alert someone that he and others had been shot at the restaurant.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Stephens was hospitalized at Denver General Hospital in fair condition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] As authorities arrived on the scene, they found two bodies in the restaurant's hallway, a third in a room off the hallway, and the fourth in the manager's office.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Crowell was sent to Denver General Hospital, where she was declared brain dead.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] She died from her injuries the next day at Aurora Regional Medical Center.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap fled the scene with $1,500 worth of cash and game tokens he stole from inside the restaurant.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He was arrested at his mother's apartment twelve hours later.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap's mother struggled with mental health issues and was later diagnosed with both schizophrenia and bipolar disorder in 1987.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] At least twice in Dunlap's junior high school years, Dunlap attempted suicide.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] When Dunlap was 14, his adoptive father asked the psychologist at Overland High School to evaluate him, and testing revealed signs of hypomania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] No further treatment or formal diagnostic was applied.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He committed several armed robberies at age 15 in 1989, using a golf club and then firearms.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He spent time incarcerated at a juvenile detention center, and due to an erratic episode, he was sent to a psychiatric hospital.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap was arrested five times on misdemeanor offenses in 1993.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap began working at the restaurant as a cook in May 1993 and was fired in July after a disagreement he had with his supervisor over schedule hours.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Acquaintances of Dunlap said he was frustrated over the firing, and told a former coworker that he planned to "get even" about the termination.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] In September 1993, Dunlap began exhibiting signs of hypomania.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] He stopped eating and sleeping, and also became progressively more wild-eyed and unkempt.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap was found guilty of four counts of first-degree murder, attempted murder, robbery, and burglary in 1996.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On May 17 of that year, Dunlap was sentenced to death and an additional 108 years.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] During his sentencing he swore repeatedly in an outburst that lasted for three minutes.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] In 2008, Dunlap filed a *habeas corpus* petition with the federal district court, arguing that his trial attorney was ineffective by not presenting a defense on his mental health issues and child abuse.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] In August 2010, this federal appeal was rejected.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Kane wrote that Dunlap was fairly tried, competently represented, and justifiably sentenced to death.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On April 16, 2012, the 10th Circuit Court of Appeals denied Dunlap's appeal of his death sentence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap's lawyers argued before the 10th Circuit that Dunlap's trial lawyers were negligent during the sentencing, by not providing evidence that Dunlap suffers from a mental illness.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] They argued that if the jurors heard evidence of Dunlap's mental illness this would spare Dunlap from being sentenced to death.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On May 1, 2013, Judge William Sylvester announced that the execution date for Dunlap would be in mid-August 2013.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On May 22, 2013, Dunlap's execution was put on hold, as Colorado Governor John Hickenlooper decided against executing Dunlap or granting him clemency and instead signed a "temporary reprieve" in 2013.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] The reprieve meant that as long as Hickenlooper was governor, Dunlap would not likely be executed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] According to Hickenlooper, one of the reasons that he did not choose full clemency was because Dunlap would have to remain segregated from the rest of the prison population.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Groups, including the NAACP, contacted Hickenlooper requesting the sparing of Dunlap's life, arguing that the death penalty is disproportionately imposed on African Americans and Hispanics.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] The reprieve also meant that unless a governor issued a new executive order, the status of the execution and clemency request would remain on hold.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Hickenlooper was constitutionally limited from running for a third term.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On November 6, 2018, Jared Polis was elected governor.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] During the campaign, Polis said he intended to sign a bill repealing the death penalty in Colorado.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Regarding the Dunlap case, Polis said he had no problem following the current law, and that he did not think it was appropriate to comment on a specific case during a campaign before actually becoming governor and reviewing the case to make an informed decision.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] On March 23, 2020, Polis signed a bill repealing the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Polis also commuted the sentences for all three men on death row, including Dunlap, to life without parole.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/1993-aurora-colorado-shooting] Dunlap remains incarcerated at the Colorado State Penitentiary in Cañon City.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 20, 2012, a mass shooting occurred inside a Century 16 movie theater in Aurora, Colorado, United States, during a midnight screening of the film *The Dark Knight Rises*.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 24-year-old James Eagan Holmes set off tear gas grenades and shot into the audience with multiple firearms.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Twelve people were fatally shot and 70 others were injured, 58 of them due to gunfire.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was arrested minutes later in his car outside the cinema.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Earlier, he had rigged his apartment with homemade explosives and incendiary devices.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] These were defused by the Arapahoe County Sheriff's Office Bomb Squad a day after the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Fearing copycat crimes, movie theaters showing the same film across the United States increased their security.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Gun sales increased in Colorado, and political debates were generated about gun control in the United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes confessed to the shooting but pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Arapahoe County prosecutors sought the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 16 of that year, Holmes was convicted of 24 counts of first-degree murder, 140 counts of attempted first-degree murder, and one count of possessing explosives.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 7, the jury deadlocked on whether to impose the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 26, Holmes was given 12 life sentences, one for every person he killed; he also received 3,318 years for the attempted murders of those he wounded and for rigging his apartment with explosives.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The shooting occurred in Theater 9 at the Century 16 multiplex (operated by Cinemark Theatres), located in the Town Center at Aurora shopping mall at 14300 E.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Police said that Holmes bought a ticket, entered the theater, and sat in the front row.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] About 20 minutes into the film, he left theater 9 through an emergency exit door beside the movie screen, with direct access to the lightly used parking area at the back of the complex, while propping the door slightly open with a plastic tablecloth holder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There were about 400 people inside theater 9.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes went to his car (which he had parked near the exit door), changed into protective clothing, and retrieved his guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] About 30 minutes into the movie, police say, around 12:30 a.m., he reentered the theater through the exit door.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was dressed in black and wore a gas mask, a load-bearing vest, a ballistic helmet, bullet-resistant leggings, a bullet-resistant throat protector, a groin protector, and tactical gloves.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He was listening to a techno radio station, which was playing the song "*Becoming Insane*" by Infected Mushroom, through a set of headphones so that he could not hear anything from people in the theater.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Initially, few in the audience considered Holmes to be a threat.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some witnesses thought he was wearing a costume, like other audience members who had dressed up for the screening.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some believed he was playing a prank, while others thought he was part of a special effects setup for the film's premiere, or a publicity stunt by the studio or theater management.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes reportedly threw one canister towards the left side of the theatre, emitting a gas or smoke, that partially obscured the audience members' vision, made their throats and skin itch, and caused eye irritation.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He fired a 12-gauge Remington 870 Express Tactical shotgun, first at the ceiling and then at the audience.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also fired a Smith & Wesson M&P15 semi-automatic rifle with a 100-round drum magazine, which eventually malfunctioned.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Finally, he fired a .40-caliber Glock 22 Gen4 handgun.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He shot first to the back of the room, and then toward people in the aisles.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A bullet passed through the wall and hit three people in adjacent theater 8, which was screening the same film.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Witnesses said the multiplex's fire alarm system began sounding soon after the attack began, and staff told people in Theater 8 to evacuate.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes fired 76 shots in the theater: 6 from the shotgun, 65 from the semi-automatic rifle, and 5 from the .40-caliber handgun.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The first phone calls to emergency services via 9-1-1 were made around midnight, prior to his attack, as can be heard in the opening statements of the prosecution, as well as the recorded transcript of his interview with the FBI.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At 12:39 a.m., after he began shooting, other victims began to call the police who arrived within 90 seconds and found three .40-caliber handgun magazines, a shotgun, and a large drum magazine on the floor of the theater.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some people reported the shooting via Twitter or text messaging rather than calling the police; officers were already at the theater by the time that the tweets were sent.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ambulances were hindered by chaos and congestion in the parking lot, and they were unable to reach the back of the complex where police had pulled the injured out through the emergency exit doors of Theatre 9.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Stephen Redfearn, one of the first police officers to arrive on the scene, sent victims to area hospitals in squad cars.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At about 12:45 a.m., police officer Jason Oviatt apprehended Holmes behind the cinema, next to his car, without resistance.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Because of his tactical clothing, Holmes was at first mistaken for another police officer.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He was described as being calm and "disconnected" during his arrest.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two federal officials said that Holmes had dyed his hair red and called himself "The Joker", although authorities later declined to confirm this.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Three days later, at his first court appearance in Centennial, Colorado, Holmes's hair appeared reddish-orange.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Later, the Colorado district attorney who prosecuted Holmes said he never called himself The Joker, and blamed the federal officials for the rumor.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The officers found several firearms in the theater and inside the shooter's car, including another Glock 22 handgun.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes was found carrying a first-aid kit and spike strips, which he later admitted in an interview he had planned to use if police either shot at or chased him.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Following his arrest, Holmes was initially jailed at the Arapahoe County Detention Center, under suicide watch.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The police interviewed more than 200 witnesses of the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Speaking on behalf of himself and FBI agent James Yacone, who was in charge of the investigation, Aurora Police Chief Dan Oates said he was confident that the shooter acted alone.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] When apprehended, Holmes told the police that he had booby-trapped his apartment with explosive devices.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Police evacuated five buildings surrounding his Aurora residence, which was about 5 mi (8 km) north of the cinema.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes' apartment complex is limited to University of Colorado Medical Center students, patients, and employees.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One day after the shooting, officials disarmed an explosive device that was wired to the apartment's front door, allowing a remote-controlled robot to enter and disable other explosives.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The apartment held more than 30 homemade grenades, wired to a control box in the kitchen and filled with at least 30 US gal (110 L) of gasoline.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Neighbors reported loud music from the apartment around midnight on the night of the massacre, and one went to his door to tell him she was calling the police; she said the door seemed to be unlocked, but she chose not to open it.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A police official said a Batman mask was found in the apartment.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 23, police finished collecting evidence from the apartment.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two days later, residents were allowed to return to the four surrounding buildings, and six days later, residents were allowed to move back into the formerly booby-trapped building.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Twelve fatalities were reported along with 70 injuries.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 58 were hit by bullets, and were reported by mainstream news as the most victims of any mass shooting in United States history.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This figure was not surpassed until the 2016 Orlando nightclub shooting, which killed 49 people and injured 58 others for a combined total of 107 casualties.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Four people's eyes were irritated by the tear gas grenades, while eight others sustained non-gunshot injuries while fleeing the theater.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The massacre was the deadliest shooting in Colorado since the Columbine High School massacre on April 20, 1999.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ten victims died at the scene and two more were pronounced dead in local hospitals.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ghawi had survived the Eaton Centre shooting in Toronto that occurred a month prior.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The injured were treated at Children's Hospital Colorado, Denver Health Medical Center, The Medical Center of Aurora, Parker Adventist Hospital, Rose Medical Center, Swedish Hospital, and University Hospital.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 25, three of the five hospitals treating victims announced they would limit medical bills or forgive them entirely.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Ashley Moser, Veronica Moser-Sullivan's mother, suffered critical injuries after being shot three times in the chest, neck, and abdomen.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] She was rendered a paraplegic due to one of the bullets lodging in her spine.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Caleb Medley, the last victim discharged, left University Hospital on September 12.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He had serious brain damage and an injury to his right eye from a shotgun blast to the head and underwent three brain surgeries.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He required a feeding tube, had severely impaired movement, and could no longer speak.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Stefan Moton was paralyzed from the chest down after a bullet went through his spine.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The Community First Foundation collected more than $5 million for a fund for victims and their families.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In September, victims and their families received surveys asking about their preferences for how collected funds should be distributed, either by dividing it equally among victims or through a needs-assessment process.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On November 16, 2012, the Aurora Victim Relief Fund announced that each family of the dead would receive $220,000.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes' booking photo was released, and he first appeared in court on July 23, 2012.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to press reports, he seemed dazed and largely unaware of his surroundings.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 30, Colorado prosecutors filed formal charges against Holmes, including 24 counts of first-degree murder, 116 counts of attempted first-degree murder and one count of illegal possession of explosives.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two charges were filed for each victim to expand the opportunities for prosecutors to obtain convictions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Colorado State District Court Judge William B.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Sylvester, who was the trial judge overseeing the case, placed a gag order on lawyers and law enforcement, sealing the court file and barring the University of Colorado from releasing public records relating to Holmes' year at the school.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Media organizations challenged the sealing of the court file.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 9, Holmes' attorneys said he is mentally ill and they needed more time to assess the nature of his illness.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The disclosure was made at a court hearing in Centennial, Colorado, where news media organizations asked a judge to unseal court documents in the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors alleged on August 24, 2012, that Holmes told a classmate he wanted to kill people four months before the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A judge ruled on August 30 that a notebook written by Holmes, in which he allegedly described a violent attack, was covered by physician–patient privilege because it was addressed to his psychiatrist.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This made it inadmissible as evidence unless Holmes' mental health became an issue in the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors dropped their request for access to the notebook on September 20, 2012.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On January 2, 2013, prosecutors and defense attorneys in the case returned to court in advance of the preliminary hearing, the public's first officially sanctioned look at the evidence, due to the gag order.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors offered their case as to why the trial should proceed, and defense lawyers argued that it should not.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] At the conclusion, Judge Sylvester decided there was enough relevant, admissible evidence to proceed to a trial.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Also on January 7, lawyers for both sides argued whether to admit four unspecified prescription bottles and immunization records investigators had seized from Holmes' apartment when they searched it in July 2012, considering doctor-patient confidentiality laws.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The judge ruled in October that prosecutors could keep the items.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On March 27, Holmes' lawyers offered a guilty plea in exchange for prosecutors not seeking the death penalty.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On April 1, the prosecution announced it had declined the offer.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Jury selection started on January 20, 2015.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On February 27, 2014, Arapahoe County District Court Judge Carlos Samour set the start of Holmes' trial for October 14.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The trial was delayed to December 8 upon a defense request for a continuance to further evaluate Holmes' mental condition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On that date, the trial was again postponed, as Holmes' lawyers asked for another continuance to further prepare their case and review the paperwork of evidence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Jury selection eventually started on January 20, 2015, after a request by Holmes' lawyers for yet another continuance was denied.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The juror selection process lasted three months and summoned 9,000 candidates, making it the largest jury summons in U.S. history.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On April 15, selection ended, with a total of nineteen women and five men serving.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There were concerns about the selection of the jurors, as at least two from the pool of twelve primary jurors, along with twelve alternates, had ties to the 1999 Columbine High School massacre: "Juror No.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 535", was the aunt of a Columbine survivor; and "Juror No.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 737", was a student there at the time and was also a former friend of the shooters.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The trial began on April 27 with opening arguments by the prosecution explaining that Holmes intentionally went to the movie theater that evening with the deliberate intent to kill as many people as possible in a mass shooting spree.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The defense opened their argument by admitting the fact that Holmes was the shooter, but said that he was mentally ill with severe schizophrenia and was never in control of his right mind.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Starting on April 28, and over the next few weeks, prosecution testimony included various survivors of the massacre and enumerated the after-effects on the survivors.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 26, the notebook Holmes mailed to his psychiatrist hours prior to the shooting was presented as evidence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] There had previously been intense debate as to whether the notebook was eligible as evidence and should be admitted, since it detailed Holmes' thoughts.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Prosecutors argued the content in Holmes' notebook, which had attack plans, proved the shooting was premeditated, while Holmes' attorneys argued that his writing indicated his mental illness.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 27, William Reid, a court-appointed psychiatrist who interviewed Holmes for a total of about 22 hours, testified that Holmes was mentally ill but legally sane.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He diagnosed him as having schizotypal personality disorder, which is characterized by constricted behavior and difficulties relating to others.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Reid and another doctor evaluated Holmes in December 2013, determining him to be legally sane, and said that his mental illness did not prevent him from forming intent and knowing the consequences of his actions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes had told Reid that he did not target children, hence why he chose a PG-13 film showing, and felt remorse when he learned children were killed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes's attorneys tried to call for a mistrial, saying that the jurors heard an unprompted opinion that complicated the legal standard for judging the sanity of a person, but the judge refused to grant the request.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 29, videos of Reid's interviews with Holmes in 2013 were shown to the court.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In the videos, Holmes described his social awkwardness and the violent, paranoid thoughts he had been having prior to the massacre.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also stated his belief that he was being followed by federal agents at the time of the massacre and hoped they would apprehend him at the theater before he could act.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to him, he transitioned from suicidal thoughts to homicidal thoughts after becoming depressed from his breakup with his girlfriend.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 8, a second psychiatrist, Jeffrey Metzner, testified that Holmes was mentally ill but legally sane when he plotted and carried out the shooting, and that he suffered from schizoaffective disorder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He interviewed Holmes for a total of 25 hours.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 9, the trial came to a standstill after three jurors were dismissed by the judge for violating orders to refrain from talking about news reports regarding the trial.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One of the jurors had begun discussions about sensitive details of the case with the other two jurors outside of the court on at least two occasions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Two days later, Holmes's attorneys requested the dismissal of a fourth juror after her brother-in-law was shot during a robbery the previous day, and other jurors had seen her crying.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Judge Carlos Samour responded that he would consider it, and agreed to the motion by dismissing her on June 15.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 17, a fifth juror was dismissed after Judge Samour was advised that she personally knew a wounded victim of the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On June 19, the prosecution called as their last witness Ashley Moser, the mother of slain victim Veronica Moser-Sullivan.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Moser was critically injured and left paralyzed by the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 9, Samour asked Holmes if he would testify in court, and advised him of his right to do so.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 10, the defense showed two videos of Holmes' behavior in his jail cell.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One video showed him running and slamming his head against the wall before sitting down while the other showed him tethered to a bed while naked, attempting to cover his head with a blanket and then a sheet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 14, closing statements were made; jury deliberations began on July 15 and continued into July 16.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 16, after deliberating for over twelve hours, the jurors found Holmes guilty on all twenty-four counts of first-degree murder, 140 counts of attempted first-degree murder, one count of possessing explosives, and a sentence enhancement of a crime of violence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] They began deciding his sentence on July 22.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The court expected the sentencing phase to last for one month.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Holmes declined to make an allocution statement.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 23, the jury ruled that Holmes acted in a cruel manner, was lying in wait, and ambushed his victims during the shooting, which constituted aggravating factors.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The jurors decided that Holmes did not intend to kill children when he opened fire.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 27, Holmes's sister testified that her brother became withdrawn from the family after they moved from Salinas to San Diego during his early teenage years.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 28, Holmes' father pleaded for his son's life, stating that he is severely mentally ill and did not deserve to die, regardless of his crimes.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He displayed photos of camping trips and family vacations with Holmes to the jury.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 30, Holmes' lawyers made a final appeal to the jurors, urging them to consider mental illness in his sentencing, despite their rejection of the insanity defense used in the trial.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The appeal for clemency was rejected on August 3, based on mitigating factors such as mental illness not outweighing aggravating factors such as the number of casualties in the massacre.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 7, Holmes was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole after jurors failed to unanimously agree on a death sentence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] One juror was opposed to sentencing Holmes to death due to his mental health issues, while two other jurors were uncertain.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Formal sentencing began on August 24 and ended on August 26.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On August 26, Samour formally sentenced Holmes to 12 consecutive life sentences without the possibility of parole for the murder charges, and an additional 3,318 years for the attempted murder and explosives possession charges.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The evening after the shooting, a candlelight vigil was held at the site in Aurora.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] President Barack Obama ordered flags at government buildings flown at half-staff, in tribute to the victims, until July 25.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Both Obama's and Mitt Romney's campaigns temporarily suspended television advertising in Colorado for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On July 22, President Obama met with victims and local and state officials and gave a nationally televised speech from Aurora.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Many world leaders sent their condolences, including Queen Elizabeth II, French President François Hollande, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Russian President Vladimir Putin, and Pope Benedict XVI.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] 's reaction to the theater shooting in Aurora, Colorado.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros., the distributor of *The Dark Knight Rises*, said it was deeply saddened by the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The studio canceled the film's gala premieres in France, Mexico, and Japan, scaled down its marketing campaign in Finland, and decided not to report box-office figures for the movie until July 23.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Some television advertisements for the film were also canceled.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Other major film studios joined Warner Bros. in withholding early box-office numbers on July 21.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros. reportedly made a "substantial" donation to Colorado's Community First Foundation to benefit victims.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Christopher Nolan, the film's director, spoke on behalf of his cast and crew and called the event "savage" and "devastating".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Christian Bale, who plays Batman in the film series, privately visited victims on July 24.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Members of the Colorado Rockies baseball team also visited victims.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Members of the Denver Broncos also called or visited individuals at the hospitals.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Warner Bros. instructed cinemas to stop screening a trailer for the film *Gangster Squad*, which preceded *The Dark Knight Rises* screenings in some cities (though not in Aurora), because it contained a scene involving the main characters shooting at a movie theater audience with machine guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The film's release date was rescheduled to January 2013, and the theater scene was replaced by a new sequence in a different setting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In the wake of the shooting, DC Comics delayed the release of *Batman Incorporated* #3, which includes a scene in which a female Leviathan agent brandishes a handgun in a classroom full of children while disguised as a schoolteacher.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Animation reportedly edited the Cartoon Network series *Beware the Batman* to make the firearms look less realistic.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Hans Zimmer, who composed the soundtrack for *The Dark Knight Rises*, recorded a choral song entitled "Aurora" in honor of the victims.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The song was sold for donations that went to a fund for the victims.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark agreed to pay any funeral expenses incurred by the deceased victims' families not covered by the Crime Victims' Compensation Fund.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark closed the entire Century Aurora 16 multiplex in the wake of the shooting but reopened January 17, 2013, with a 40-minute ceremony led by Aurora Mayor Steve Hogan, followed by a showing of *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] As of 2020, Cinemark Theatres has not released any photographs or video evidence.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Soon after the shooting, police departments and cinemas across the United States and around the world increased security for fear of copycat incidents.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In New York City, police officers were deployed to theaters screening the new film.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The National Association of Theatre Owners distributed checklists from the U.S.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Department of Homeland Security to its members and said in a July 21 statement that members were "working closely with local law enforcement agencies and reviewing security procedures".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] AMC Theatres announced it would "not allow any guests into our theatres in costumes that make other guests feel uncomfortable and we will not permit face-covering masks or fake weapons inside our buildings".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Three victims sued Cinemark Theatres in the U.S.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] District Court for the District of Colorado on September 21, 2012, for the company's alleged negligence in failing to provide adequate safety and security measures.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In response, Cinemark's representation filed a motion to dismiss on September 27, 2012, on the grounds that there was no liability under Colorado law for failure to prevent an unforeseeable criminal act.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Cinemark's motion quoted extensively from the landmark California appellate opinion that held McDonald's had no duty of care to prevent the 1984 San Ysidro McDonald's massacre.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On October 30, 2012, the court hearing the criminal case against Holmes denied a motion by some of the survivors that would have let them access sealed evidence for review in their civil action against the theater chain.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Magistrate Judge Michael Hegarty issued a recommendation that most of the claims be dismissed, as they were not allowable under Colorado law.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] He also said claims alleging violations of the Colorado Premises Liability Act could proceed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Brooke Jackson stated that for theaters today, "One might reasonably believe that a mass shooting incident in a theater was likely enough (that is, not just a possibility) to be a foreseeable next step in the history of such acts by deranged individuals".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Attorney Christina Habas, who represents several theater victims, has said, "We essentially don't have a single photograph, a single piece of evidence that we can show to a jury".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In June 2016, a federal judge dismissed the last claims in the lawsuit.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In a separate lawsuit in state court, Cinemark was sued by families of the victims, who alleged the theater should have taken greater measures to prevent such a shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In May 2016, after years of legal debate, a jury took three hours to deliver a unanimous verdict that the theater chain was not liable to any degree.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The judge allowed Cinemark Theatres to submit a bill of costs to the plaintiffs to recover expenses due to the litigation, as Colorado state law allows for prevailing parties.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In September 2016, Cinemark dropped all claims for reimbursement of legal fees.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On January 14, 2013, Chantel Blunk, the estranged wife and widow of victim Jonathan Blunk, sued the University of Colorado in federal court.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] She alleged that a school psychiatrist could have prevented the slaughter by having Holmes detained after he admitted he "fantasized about killing a lot of people".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] This type of lawsuit had been anticipated in an August 2012 article co-authored by bioethicist Arthur Caplan which discussed the applicability of the landmark California Supreme Court decision in *Tarasoff v.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Regents of the University of California* (1976) to the facts of the Aurora shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A grassroots community center, Aurora Strong Resilience Center, was established by community leaders, elected officials, and mental health professionals, as a response to the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The center offers therapy for people who experienced traumatic stress from the theater shooting, and also people who were victims of other crimes and refugees who experienced a traumatic event in their country of origin before coming to the United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Colorado gun sales spiked after the shooting, with the number of background checks for people seeking to purchase a firearm in the state increasing to 2,887, up 43% from the previous week.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Gun sales in Washington, Florida, California, and Georgia also increased.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The shooting reignited the political debate on gun control, with one issue being the "easy access" Holmes had two semi-automatic rifles and high-capacity magazines, which were banned federally from 1994 to 2004.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The results of a survey released on July 30, 2012, by the Pew Research Center suggested the incident did not change Americans' views on the issue.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On March 20, 2013, Colorado governor John Hickenlooper signed House bill 13-1224, which made the sale, transferal, or possession of magazines holding 15 rounds or more illegal unless said magazines were lawfully owned prior to July 1, 2013.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The law also specified that firearms with a tubular magazine which are either chambered in .22 rimfire or operated by lever action are exempt from this regulation, as are magazines "permanently altered" to limit the capacity to 15 or fewer.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] On May 6, 2026, the United States Department of Justice sued the state of Colorado over the 2013 law banning high-capacity magazines, alleging it violates the Second Amendment.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In 2015, a campaign titled "No Notoriety" was started by the parents of Alexander Teves, who died in the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] According to Teves' father, the campaign's incentive is to encourage media outlets to limit the usage of the suspect's name and photos when reporting about the Aurora shooting, as well as other mass shootings that receive national media coverage.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] In an interview on CNN, Teves' parents said they and the relatives of other victims believe the mass media coverage of Holmes' name and photo may inspire others to commit mass shootings for notoriety.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The Century 16 theater where the shooting occurred was rebranded as the Century Aurora theater by its parent company Cinemark Theatres.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Despite heavy criticism from families and loved ones of victims, the theater was not demolished and reopened to the public after cleaning and renovation on January 25, 2013, 6 months after the shooting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The reopening ceremony, which was boycotted by opponents of the theater's reopening, included a memorial service and a screening of *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Theater room nine, where the actual shooting occurred, was combined with an adjoining room into a new XD theater room.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] A memorial to the victims of the attack was installed near Aurora Municipal Center, some 850 m (929.57 yd) from the theater, and dedicated on July 19, 2018, one day before the sixth anniversary of the attack.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] It consists of a park-like dell with 83 abstract birds, one for each victim.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] Thirteen of the birds, with translucent wings, are on a center column and represent the thirteen deceased victims, including the unborn child.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/2012-aurora-theater-shooting] The memorial, titled "Ascentiate", was designed by artist Douwe Blumberg.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The **.22 long rifle** (**.22LR**), also known as the **5.7×15mmR**, is a long-established variety of .22 caliber rimfire ammunition originating from the United States.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] It is used in a wide range of firearms, including rifles, pistols, revolvers, and submachine guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] It is a well-established small-game round but is not typically used for hunting larger game, as it lacks the necessary stopping power.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] In terms of quantities sold, the .22 Long Rifle is by far the most common ammunition that is currently manufactured and sold in the world.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Common uses include hunting and shooting sports.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Ammunition produced in .22 Long Rifle is effective at short ranges, has little recoil, and is inexpensive to purchase, making it ideal for plinking and marksmanship training.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Stevens Arms & Tool Company introduced the .22 long rifle cartridge in 1887.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The round owes its origin to the .22 BB Cap of 1845 and the .22 short of 1857.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] It combined the case of the .22 long of 1871 with a 40-grain (2.6 g) bullet, giving it a longer overall length, a higher muzzle velocity, and superior performance as a hunting and target round, rendering .22 extra long cartridges obsolete.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 LR uses a heeled bullet, which means that the bullet is the same diameter as the case, and has a narrower "heel" portion that fits inside the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] It is one of the few cartridges accepted by a wide variety of rifles and handguns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 LR cartridge is popular with both novice shooters and experts.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Its minimal recoil and relatively low noise make it an ideal cartridge for recreational shooting, small-game hunting, and pest control.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Military cadets and others commonly use .22 LR cadet rifles for basic firearms and marksmanship training.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The Boy Scouts of America use it for the rifle shooting merit badge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The cartridge's low recoil makes it ideal for introductory firearms courses.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Novice shooters can be surprised or frightened by the noise and recoil of more powerful rounds.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Beginners shooting firearms beyond their comfort level frequently develop a habit of flinching in an attempt to counter anticipated recoil.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The resulting habit impedes correct posture and follow-through at the most critical phase of the shot and is difficult to correct.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] With high recoil eliminated, other errors in marksmanship technique are easier to identify and correct.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Many handgun manufacturers offer an upper pistol conversion kit to allow the pistol to shoot .22 LR ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] These conversions allow shooters to practice inexpensively while retaining the handling characteristics of their chosen firearms (with reduced recoil and muzzle blast).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Additionally, .22 LR cartridge conversion kits allow practice at indoor ranges which prohibit high-power firearms.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Owners of guns that use gas systems, such as AR-15 sport style rifles, normally avoid firing non-plated .22 LR cartridge ammunition, as the use of non-plated ammunition may cause lead fouling of the gas port inside the barrel and costly gunsmithing procedures.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] This can usually be mitigated by swapping the conversion kit for the standard bolt carrier group and firing several full-powered rounds to clear the gas port and tube of any accumulated lead fouling.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] While not 100% effective, the extremely hot, incandescent gases produced by centerfire rifle ammunition will help clear any lead fouling from .22 LR ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A wide variety of .22 LR ammunition is commercially available, and it varies widely in price and performance.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Bullet weights among commercially available ammunition range from 20 to 60 grains (1.3 to 3.9 g), and velocities vary from 575 to 1,750 ft/s (175 to 533 m/s). .22 LR is the least costly firearm cartridge ammunition available around the world.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Promotional loads for plinking can be purchased in bulk for significantly less cost than precision target rounds.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The low cost of ammunition has a substantial effect on the popularity of the .22 LR.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] For this reason, rimfire cartridges are commonly used for target practice.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] .22 LR cartridges are commonly packaged in boxes of 50 or 100 rounds, and are often sold by the 'brick', a carton containing either 10 boxes of 50 rounds or loose cartridges totaling 500 rounds, or the 'case' containing 10 bricks totaling 5,000 rounds.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Annual production is estimated at 2–2.5 billion rounds by some.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The NSSF estimates that a large percentage of the US production of 10 billion cartridges is composed of .22 LR.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Despite the high production figures there have occasionally been shortages of .22 LR cartridge in the contiguous United States, most notably during the U.S. ammunition shortage of the late 2000s and early 2010s.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 LR is effective to 150 yd (140 m), though practical ranges tend to be less.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] After 150 yd (140 m), the ballistics of the round are such that it will be difficult to compensate for the large "drop".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The relatively short effective range, low report, and light recoil have made it a favorite for use as a target-practice cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The cartridge's accuracy is good but not exceptional; other cartridges can achieve the same or better accuracy.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A contributing factor in rifles is the transition of even a high-velocity cartridge projectile from supersonic to subsonic within 100 yd (91 m).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] As the bullet slows, the shock wave generated by supersonic travel overtakes it, disrupting its flight path and causing minor but measurable inaccuracies.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] When zeroed for 100 yards (91 m), the arc-trajectory of the standard high-velocity .22 LR with a 40 gr (2.6 g) bullet has a 2.7-inch (69 mm) rise at 50 yards (46 m), and a 10.8-inch (27 cm) drop at 150 yards (140 m).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A .22 LR rifle needs to be zeroed for 75 yards (69 m) to avoid overshooting small animals like squirrels and rabbits at intermediate distances.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] As a hunting cartridge, rimfires are mainly used to kill small game animals up to the size of coyotes.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Although proper shot placement can kill larger animals such as deer or hog, it is not recommended because its low power may not guarantee a humane kill.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] In 2013, an elephant was killed by multiple shots from a .22 LR rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Because a .22 LR bullet is less powerful than most larger cartridges, its danger to humans is often underestimated.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A .22 LR bullet is easily capable of killing or injuring humans.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Even after flying 400 yards (370 m), a .22 bullet is still traveling at about 500 ft/s (150 m/s).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Ricochets are more common in .22 LR projectiles than for more powerful cartridges as the combination of unjacketed lead and moderate velocities allows the projectile to deflect – not penetrate or disintegrate – when hitting hard objects at a glancing angle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A .22 LR bullet can ricochet off the surface of water at a low angle of aim.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Severe injury may result to a person or object in the line of fire on the opposite shore, several hundred yards or meters away.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A .22 LR bullet is capable of traveling 2,000 yards (1,800 m), which is more than 1 mile (1.6 km).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Rimfire bullets are generally either plain lead with a wax coating (for subsonic-velocity or standard-velocity loads) or plated with copper or gilding metal (for high-velocity or hyper-velocity loads).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The thin copper layer on a plated bullet functions as a lubricant, reducing friction between the bullet and the barrel and thus reducing barrel wear.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Plating also prevents oxidation of the lead bullet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Lead tends to oxidize if stored for long periods.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Subsonic rounds have a muzzle velocity of less than the speed of sound (about 1,080 ft/s or 330 m/s).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] These rounds are sometimes equipped with extra-heavy bullets of 45–60-grain (2.9–3.9 g) to improve the terminal ballistics of the slower projectile.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Conversely, these rounds may contain little more than a primer and an extra-light bullet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Some shooters favor subsonic rounds for slightly improved accuracy and reduced noise.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Supersonic rounds produce a loud crack which can scare away animals when hunting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Accuracy is reportedly improved with subsonic rounds because a supersonic bullet (or projectile) that slows from supersonic to subsonic speed undergoes drastic aerodynamic changes in this transonic zone that might adversely affect the stability and accuracy of the bullet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Because the speed of sound in air at 68 °F (20 °C) is about 1,115 ft/s (340 m/s), the subsonic round's muzzle velocity is slightly below the speed of sound under many hunting conditions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] However, under cold air conditions at 32 °F (0 °C), the speed of sound drops to 1,088 ft/s (332 m/s), approximately muzzle velocity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Hence, a "subsonic" round used below this temperature may be supersonic, and during the transition from supersonic to subsonic velocity, it may become unstable, reducing accuracy.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] To counteract this, some cartridge manufacturers have lowered the speed of their subsonic ammunition to 1,030 ft/s (310 m/s) or less.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Various combinations of subsonic rounds and semiautomatic .22 LR firearms result in unreliable action cycling due to insufficient recoil energy.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Some subsonic rounds use heavier bullets (achieving lower velocities) to ensure, as a result of increased bullet mass, that enough energy is produced to cycle common blowback actions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] As an example, the Aguila .22 LR SSS (sniper sub-sonic) round, has a 60 gr (3.9 g) bullet on a .22 short case, providing the cartridge the same overall dimensions as a .22 long rifle round.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] However, other problems may be encountered: the heavier, longer bullet of the Aguila cartridge requires a faster barrel twist (as determined by the Greenhill formula) to ensure the bullet remains stable in flight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Two performance classes of .22 rimfire subsonic rounds exist.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Some subsonic rounds, such as various .22 short and .22 long "CB" rounds, give about 700 ft/s (210 m/s) velocity with a 29 gr (1.9 g) bullet providing relatively low impact energy 30 ft⋅lbf (41 J) at the muzzle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] These may not use any, or only small amounts of gunpowder, and have the characteristics of rounds intended only for indoor training or target practice rather than hunting.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Where these are in .22 LR form, it is only to aid feeding in firearms designed for the cartridge, rather than older .22 CB shooting gallery rifles.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The Aguila SSS has a velocity of 950 ft/s (290 m/s) using a 60 gr (3.9 g) bullet with 120 ft⋅lbf (160 J) of energy, which is equivalent to many high velocity .22 long rifle rounds using standard 40 gr (2.6 g) bullets.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Other heavy-bullet subsonic rounds perform similarly and are intended for hunting small game or controlling dangerous animals while avoiding excessive noise.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The velocity of standard-velocity .22 LR rounds varies between manufacturers.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Some standard velocity ammo may be slightly supersonic-around 1,125 ft/s (343 m/s), other ammo such as CCI Standard Velocity .22 LR ammunition is rated at 1,070 ft/s (330 m/s).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Most standard velocity ammo has a bullet weight of 40 gr (2.6 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Standard-velocity cartridges generate near or slightly supersonic velocities.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] These rounds generally do not develop these velocities in handguns because their short barrels do not take full advantage of the slower burning powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 long rifle round was originally loaded with black powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The first smokeless powder loads were intended to match the standard velocity of the original black-powder rounds.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Smokeless powder is more efficient than black powder, and the cartridge cases could hold more powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Many .22 LR cartridges use bullets lighter than the standard 40 gr (2.6 g) and are fired at even higher velocities.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Hyper-velocity bullets usually weigh around 30 to 32 gr (1.9 to 2.1 g) and can have a muzzle velocity of 1,400 to 1,800 feet per second (430 to 550 m/s).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] This higher velocity is partially due to the use of lighter bullets.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The CCI Stinger was the first hyper-velocity .22 LR cartridge and provided a significant increase in velocity and energy over standard rimfire rounds.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] This slightly longer case length can cause feeding and ejection issues in some match grade guns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] A powder with a slower burning rate is used to make the most use of the length of a rifle barrel.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Most .22 long rifle powders increase velocity up to about 19 in (480 mm) of the barrel.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The powder used in the .22 Long Rifle Stinger increased the velocity in the longest .22 caliber barrel length that is used in testing by the NRA, which is 24 in (610 mm).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Later on, other makers introduced hyper-velocity rounds based on the long rifle case, with lighter bullets in the 30 gr (1.9 g) weight range and slow-burning rifle powder loads.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The overall length of many of these cartridges was less than the overall length of the standard 40 gr (2.6 g) long rifle cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] One example is the Remington Viper and another is the Federal Spitfire.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The CCI Velocitor hyper-velocity round uses the standard long rifle case size and a standard-weight 40 gr (2.6 g) bullet with a proprietary hollow-point design to enhance expansion and trauma.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] This cartridge has a muzzle velocity of 1,435 ft/s (437 m/s) and matches the overall length of the standard long rifle cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Special .22LR caliber shot cartridges, usually loaded with No.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] These are often called "snake shot," "bird shot", and "rat-shot" due to their use in very short range pest control.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Such rounds have either a longer brass case that is crimped closed or a translucent plastic "bullet" that contains the shot and shatters upon firing.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] During World War II, a full metal jacket bullet version of the .22 LR was developed as the T-42 for the suppressed High Standard HDM pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The US Army Air Corps procured the Savage Model 24 .22 LR/.410 combination gun as an air crew survival weapon included in the E series of survival and sustenance kits, primarily to forage for game for food.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 LR full metal jacket bullet ammunition was issued with these firearms for military use to comply with treaty restrictions on expanding bullets.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The 1961 Army and Air Force technical manual for small-arms ammunition lists the jacketed cartridge as the M24.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Tracer ammunition is also available in .22 long rifle rimfire.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The traditional .22 rimfire cartridges (BB, CB, short, long, long rifle, and extra long) differ in construction from more modern cartridges in the way the bullet is constructed and held in the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Bullets for traditional .22 rimfires are the same outside diameter as the case but are constructed with a narrower cupped "heel" on the base of the bullet, which is inserted into the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The case mouth is then crimped around the bullet's heel, leaving most of the bullet-bearing surface exposed to contact the barrel of the gun.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The bearing surface of .22 rimfire bullets is often lubricated and exposed to contamination.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] This was a common design in the early black powder cartridge era.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The heeled bullet cartridge is considered weaker than the uniform diameter bullet cartridge, which encloses the bearing surface of the bullet within the cartridge neck.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The overall reliability of heeled-bullet rimfire ammunition is high but lower than that of most centerfire ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 long rifle uses a straight-walled case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Depending on the type and feed mechanism employed, a firearm chambered for .22 long rifle may also be able to safely chamber and fire shorter rimfire cartridges, including the .22 BB, .22 CB, .22 short, .22 long.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 long rifle may also be used in firearms chambered for the obsolete .22 extra long.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Today, rimfire rounds are mainly used for hunting small pests, for sports shooting, for plinking, and for inexpensive training.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22LR is the choice for several shooting events: biathlon, bullseye, plus divisions of benchrest shooting, metallic silhouette and pin shooting, most high school, collegiate, Boy Scouts of America, Project Appleseed, 4H shooting events, and many others.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] It is also used in the precision Rifle and Pistol shooting events at the Olympic Games.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Good quality rimfire ammunition can be quite accurate.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The main advantages are low cost, low recoil, low noise, and high accuracy-to-cost ratio.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The main disadvantage is its low power; it is better suited for use on small game and other small animals.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] As a defensive cartridge, it is considered inadequate by many, though the small size allows very lightweight, easily concealable handguns which can be carried in circumstances where anything larger would be impractical.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Despite their limitations, people can use .22 LR pistols and rifles for defense, and they are common simply because they are prevalent, inexpensive, and widely available.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Most semiautomatic rifles firing .22 LR cartridges will often only work properly with standard or high-velocity rimfire ammunition, as the low recoil of subsonic rounds is insufficient to cycle the weapon's action.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Rifles with manual actions do not have this problem.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Due to the low bolt thrust of the .22 LR cartridge, most self-loading firearms chambered for the cartridge use the direct blowback operation system.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The tiny case of the .22 LR and the subsonic velocities (when using subsonic ammunition) make it well-suited for use with a firearm suppressor (also known as silencers or sound moderators).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Where firearm suppressors are only minimally restricted, a .22 LR firearm with a suppressor is often favored for plinking, as it does not require hearing protection or cause noise pollution.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Local government agencies sometimes use suppressed rimfire weapons for animal control, since dangerous animals or pests can be dispatched in populated areas without causing undue alarm.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The .22 LR has also seen limited usage by police and military snipers.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Its main advantage in this role is its low noise, but it is usually limited to urban operations because of its short range.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] One study suggests that a single head/torso shot suffices, more often than not.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The Israeli military used a suppressed .22 LR rifle in the 1990s for riot control and to "eliminate disturbing dogs prior to operations"; however, it is now used less often as it is more lethal than previously suspected.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Some other examples include the use of suppressed High Standard HDM pistols by the American OSS, which was the predecessor organization of the CIA.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Francis Gary Powers was issued a suppressed High Standard for the flight in which he was shot down.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Suppressed Ruger MK II pistols were used by the US Navy SEALs in the 1990s.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] .22 long rifle maximum C.I.P. cartridge dimensions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 406mm (1:16 in), six grooves, land width = 2.16mm, Ø lands = 5.38mm, Ø grooves = 5.58mm.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] (Commission Internationale Permanente pour l'Epreuve des Armes à Feu Portatives) rulings, the .22 long rifle can handle up to 170.00 MPa (24,656 psi) Pmax piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] In C.I.P. regulated countries, every rifle cartridge combo has to be proofed at 125% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Because the .22 long rifle round commonly uses a heeled lead or lightly plated bullet, the nominal bullet diameter is larger than the nominal bore diameter.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Lead bullets with a diameter equal to or slightly smaller than the barrel's groove diameter may allow exhaust gases to pass, leading to excessive lead fouling.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] SAAMI specifies a nominal bullet diameter of 0.2255 with a tolerance of -0.004, while the specified bore diameter is 0.222.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] In practice, 0.224 or slightly larger bullets are common, with barrel groove diameters commonly around 0.223.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/22-rimfire] Note: actual velocities depend on many factors, such as the barrel length of a given firearm and the manufacturer of a given batch of ammunition, and will vary widely in practice.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The **.223 Remington,** also known as **223 Remington** by SAAMI and **223 Rem.** by the C.I.P., (pronounced "two-two-three") is a rimless, bottlenecked, centerfire intermediate cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] It was developed in 1957 by Remington Arms and Fairchild Industries for the U.S.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Continental Army Command of the United States Army as part of a project to create a small-caliber, high-velocity firearm.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Firing a .2245 in (5.70 mm) projectile, the .223 Remington is considered one of the most popular common-use cartridges and is used by a wide range of semi-automatic and manual-action rifles.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The development of the cartridge, which eventually became the .223 Remington, was linked to the creation of a new small-caliber, high-velocity (SCHV) combat rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Work on a rifle and cartridge to meet the requirements of the U.S.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Continental Army Command (CONARC) began in 1957.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Fairchild Industries, Remington Arms, Winchester, and several engineers (including Eugene Stoner of ArmaLite, who was invited to scale down the AR-10 (7.62×51mm NATO) design), contributed.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Stoner and Sierra Bullet's Frank Snow began work on the .222 Remington cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Using a ballistic calculator, they determined that a 55-grain bullet would have to be fired at 3,300 ft/s to achieve the 500-yard performance necessary.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Robert Hutton (technical editor of *Guns and Ammo* magazine) started the development of a powder load to reach the 3,300 ft/s goal.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] He used DuPont IMR4198, IMR3031, and an Olin powder to work up loads.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Testing was done with a Remington 722 rifle with a 22" Apex barrel.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] During a public demonstration, the round successfully penetrated the US steel helmet as required, but testing also showed chamber pressures to be too high.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Stoner contacted both Winchester and Remington about increasing the case capacity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Remington created a larger cartridge called the .222 Special.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] This cartridge is loaded with DuPont IMR4475 powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] During parallel testing of the T44E4 (future M14) and the ArmaLite AR-15 in 1958, the T44E4 experienced 16 failures per 1,000 rounds fired compared to 6.1 for the ArmaLite AR-15.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Because of several different .222 caliber cartridges that were being developed for the SCHV project, the .222 Special was renamed .223 Remington.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In May 1959, a report was produced stating that five- to seven-man squads armed with ArmaLite AR-15 rifles have a higher hit probability than 11-man squads armed with the M14 rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] At an Independence Day picnic, Air Force General Curtis LeMay tested the ArmaLite AR-15 and was very impressed with it.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] He ordered a number of them to replace M2 carbines that were in use by the Air Force.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In November of that year, testing at Aberdeen Proving Ground showed the ArmaLite AR-15 failure rate had declined to 2.5/1,000, resulting in the ArmaLite AR-15 being approved for more extensive trials.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In 1961, marksmanship testing compared the AR-15 and M14; 43% of ArmaLite AR-15 shooters achieved Expert, while only 22% of M14 rifle shooters did.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In July 1962, operational testing ended with a recommendation for the adoption of the ArmaLite AR-15 rifle chambered in .223 Remington.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In September 1963, the .223 Remington cartridge was officially accepted and named "Cartridge, 5.56 mm ball, M193".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The following year, the ArmaLite AR-15 was adopted by the United States Army as the M16 rifle, and it would later become the standard U.S. military rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The specification included a Remington-designed bullet and the use of IMR4475 powder, which resulted in a muzzle velocity of 3,250 ft/s and a chamber pressure of 52,000 psi.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In the spring of 1962, Remington submitted the specifications of the .223 Remington to the Sporting Arms and Ammunition Manufacturers' Institute (SAAMI).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In December 1963, Remington introduced its first rifle chambered for .223 Remington a Model 760 rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The .223 Remington has a 1.87 mL (28.8 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Americans would define the shoulder angle at alpha/2 = 23 degrees.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 305 mm (1 in 12 in), 6 grooves, Ø lands = 5.56 millimetres (0.219 in), Ø grooves = 5.69 millimetres (0.224 in), land width = 1.88 millimetres (0.074 in) and the primer type is small rifle.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] According to the official CIP rulings, the .223 Remington can handle up to 430.00 MPa (62,366 psi) Pmax piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In CIP-regulated countries, every rifle cartridge combination has to be proofed at 125% of this maximum CIP pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] This means that .223 Remington chambered arms in CIP-regulated countries are as of 2016 proof tested at 537.50 MPa (77,958 psi) PE piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] This is equal to the NATO maximum service pressure guideline for the 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .223 Remington is set at 379.212 MPa (55,000 psi), piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Remington submitted .223 Remington specifications to SAAMI in 1964.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In 1980, the .223 Remington was transformed into a new cartridge and designated 5.56×45mm NATO (SS109 or M855).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The external dimensional specifications of .223 Remington and 5.56×45mm NATO brass cases are nearly identical.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] When hand-loaded, care is taken to look for pressure signs as 5.56×45mm NATO cases may produce higher pressures with the same type of powder and bullet as compared to .223 Remington cases.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Sierra provides separate loading sections for .223 Remington and 5.56×45mm NATO and also recommends different loads for bolt-action rifles as compared to semiautomatic rifles.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Remington submitted the specifications for the .223 Remington cartridge in 1964 to SAAMI.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The original pressure for the .223 Remington was 52,000 psi with DuPont IMR Powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] A higher pressure of 55,000 psi (379 MPa) resulted from the change from IMR to Olin Ball powder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The official name for .223 Remington in the US Army is cartridge 5.56x45mm ball, M193.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] If a 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge is loaded into a chamber intended to use .223 Remington, the bullet will be in contact with the rifling and the forcing cone is very tight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] This generates a much higher pressure than .223 Remington chambers are designed for.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Chamber pressures obtained using different methods are not comparable.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The pressure limits for .223 Rem and 5.56×45mm NATO are very similar, if using similar measurement methodologies.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The .223 Remington and 5.56×45mm NATO barrel chamberings are not the same according to Clymer, with the 5.56 NATO chamber having generally slightly larger dimensions.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] A brochure from "Forster Products" claims that while the headspace gauge for .223 Rem is 1.4636/1.4666/1.4696 for Go/NoGo/Field, the gauge is 1.4636/1.4736 for Min/Max on 5.56 NATO.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The brochure goes on to claim that this could mean a premature contact with rifling with 5.56 ammunition if fired from a .223 chamber.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] However, the 2025 SAAMI specification for the headspace dimension on .223 Rem is the same as what Forster claimed for 5.56 NATO: 1.4636 to 1.4736.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In any case, the premature contact allegation is likely not based on headspace differences, but on the lede length and angle difference between the two chambers, with 5.56 NATO having a shallower and longer lede.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] By observation, 5.56×45mm NATO ammunition is not as accurate as .223 Remington in many of the AR-type rifles extant, even with the same bullet weight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The .223 Wylde chamber specification developed by Bill Wylde solves this problem by using the external dimensions and lead angle as found in the military 5.56×45mm NATO cartridge and the 0.224 inch freebore diameter as found in the civilian SAAMI .223 Remington cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] It was designed to increase the accuracy of 5.56×45mm NATO ammunition to that of .223 Remington.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Other companies also have chamber designs that increase 5.56×45mm NATO accuracy.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Andrew of LuckyGunner LLC has collected 8 different chamber dimensions from various reamer companies, including .223 Rem, .223 Wylde, and 5.56.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] He also emphasizes that manufacturing differences will make each actual chamber dimensionally different from others.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] In addition, he tested 5.56 NATO ammunition in .223 Rem chambers and failed to find dangerous levels of pressure increase.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] NATO chose a 178-mm (1-in-7) rifling twist rate for the 5.56×45mm NATO chambering.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The SS109/M855 5.56×45mm NATO ball cartridge requires a minimum 228 mm (1-in-9) twist rate, while adequately stabilizing the longer NATO L110/M856 5.56×45mm NATO tracer projectile requires an even faster 178 mm (1-in-7) twist rate.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The table contains some estimated pressures based on normal proofing practice and on the known increases in pressure caused by bullet setback (which is a similar occurrence with regard to pressure).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The proof pressure of M197 is 70,000 psi.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Barrel length helps determine a specific cartridge's muzzle velocity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] A longer barrel typically yields a greater muzzle velocity, while a shorter barrel yields a lower one.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The first AR-15 rifles used a barrel length of 20".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] The .223 Remington has become one of the most popular cartridges.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] It is used in a wide range of semiautomatic and manual-action rifles and even handguns, such as the Colt AR-15, Ruger Mini-14, Remington Model 700.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] For example, the cartridge has become widely used in the US, significantly reducing the prevalence of other similar .22 caliber center-fire varmint rifle cartridges such as the .22 Hornet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] It is commercially loaded with 0.224-inch (5.7 mm) diameter jacketed bullets, with weights ranging from 35 to 85 grains (2.27 to 5.8 g), with the most common loading by far being 55 gr (3.6 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/223-remington] Ninety-grain and 95-grain (6.2 g) Sierra Matchking bullets are available for reloaders.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The **.40 S&W** is a rimless pistol cartridge developed jointly by American firearms manufacturers Smith & Wesson and Winchester in 1990.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was developed as a law enforcement cartridge designed to duplicate the performance of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's (FBI) reduced-velocity 10mm Auto cartridge which could be retrofitted into medium-frame (9 mm size) semi-automatic handguns.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] It uses 0.40-inch-diameter (10 mm) bullets typically ranging in weight from 105 to 200 grains (6.8 to 13.0 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] In the aftermath of the 1986 FBI Miami shootout, in which two FBI special agents were killed and five wounded, the FBI started the process of testing 9×19mm Parabellum and .45 ACP ammunition in preparation to replace its standard-issue revolver with a semi-automatic pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The semi-automatic pistol offered two advantages over the revolver: increased ammunition capacity and increased ease of reloading during a gunfight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The FBI was satisfied with the performance of its .38 Special +P 158 gr (10.2 g) lead semi-wadcutter hollowpoint (LSWCHP) cartridge ("FBI load") based on decades of dependable performance.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Ammunition for the new semi-automatic pistol had to deliver terminal performance equal or superior to the .38 Special FBI load.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The FBI developed a series of practically oriented tests involving eight test events that they believed reasonably represented the kinds of situations that FBI agents commonly encountered in shooting incidents.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] During tests of the 9×19mm and .45 ACP ammunition, the unit chief of the FBI Firearms Training Unit, John Hall, decided to include tests of the 10mm Auto cartridge, supplying his own Colt Delta Elite 10mm semi-automatic, and personally hand-loaded ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The FBI's tests revealed that a 170–180 gr (11.0–11.7 g) JHP 10mm bullet, propelled between 900–1,000 ft/s (270–300 m/s), achieved desired terminal performance without the heavy recoil associated with conventional 10mm ammunition (1,300–1,400 ft/s (400–430 m/s)).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The FBI contacted Smith & Wesson and requested that it design a handgun to FBI specifications, based on the existing large-frame Smith & Wesson Model 4506 .45 ACP handgun, that would reliably function with the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] During this collaboration with the FBI, S&W realized that downsizing the 10mm full-power to meet the FBI's medium-velocity specification meant less powder and more airspace in the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] They found that by removing the airspace they could shorten the 10mm case enough to fit within their medium-frame 9mm handguns and load it with a 180 gr (11.7 g) JHP bullet to produce ballistic performance identical to the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] S&W then teamed with Winchester to produce a new cartridge, the .40 S&W.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] It uses a small pistol primer whereas the 10mm cartridge uses a large pistol primer.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge debuted January 17, 1990, along with the new Smith & Wesson Model 4006 pistol, although it was several months before the pistols were available for purchase.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Austrian manufacturer Glock Ges.m.b.H. were commercially available ahead of Smith & Wesson in 1990, with pistols chambered in .40 S&W (the Glock 22 and Glock 23) which were announced a week before the 4006.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Glock's rapid introduction was aided by its engineering of a pistol chambered in 10mm Auto, the Glock 20, only a short time earlier.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Since the .40 S&W uses the same bore diameter and case head as the 10mm Auto, it was merely a matter of adapting the 10mm design to the shorter 9×19mm Parabellum frames.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The new guns and ammunition were an immediate success, and pistols in the new caliber were adopted by several law enforcement agencies around the nation, including the FBI, which adopted the Glock pistol in .40 S&W in May 1997.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The popularity of the .40 S&W accelerated with the passage of the now-expired Federal Assault Weapons Ban of 1994, which prohibited sales of pistol or rifle magazines that could hold more than ten cartridges, regardless of caliber.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Several U.S. states, and a number of local governments, also banned or regulated so-called "high-capacity" magazines.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] As a result, many new firearm buyers limited to purchasing pistols with a maximum magazine capacity of 10 rounds chose pistols in the .40 S&W chambering instead of smaller-diameter cartridges such as the 9×19mm (9mm Luger or 9mm Parabellum).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W case length and overall cartridge length are shortened, but other dimensions except for case web and wall thickness remain identical to the 10mm Auto.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Both cartridges headspace on the mouth of the case.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Thus in a semi-auto, they are not interchangeable.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Fired from a 10mm semi-auto, the .40 Smith & Wesson cartridge will headspace on the extractor and the bullet will jump a 0.142 inches (3.6 mm) freebore just like a .38 Special fired from a .357 Magnum revolver.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] If the cartridge is not held by the extractor, the chances for a ruptured primer are great.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Smith & Wesson does make a double-action revolver (the Model 610) that can fire either cartridge via use of moon clips.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] A single-action revolver in the .38–40 chambering can also fire .40 or 10mm rounds provided it is equipped with a correctly sized cylinder.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Some .40 caliber handguns can be converted to 9mm with a special purpose-made barrel, magazine change, and other parts.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] In 2015, the FBI announced they were going back to 9mm ammunition, citing advancements in ballistic technology and increased accuracy in a gunfight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The FBI also found that .40 S&W rounds were causing excessive wear on pistols and were harder to control for some agents.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] This has caused a substantial contribution to the .40 S&W's decline in popularity with law enforcement in the US.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has a 1.25 ml (19.3 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 406 millimetres (16.0 in), with 6 grooves, land diameter 9.91 mm, groove diameter 10.17 mm, and land width 3.05 mm, and the primer type is small pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] According to the official C.I.P. guidelines, the .40 S&W case can handle up to 225 MPa (32,600 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] In C.I.P.-regulated countries, every pistol/cartridge combo has to be proofed at 130% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .40 S&W is set at 241.32 MPa (35,001 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge has been popular with law enforcement agencies in the United States, Canada, Australia, and Brazil.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] While possessing nearly identical accuracy, drift and drop as the 9mm Parabellum, it has an energy advantage over the 9mm Parabellum and .45 ACP, and a more manageable recoil than the 10mm Auto cartridge.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Marshall & Sanow (and other hydrostatic shock proponents) contend that with good jacketed hollow point bullets, the more energetic loads for the .40 S&W can also create hydrostatic shock in human-sized living targets.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Based on the ideal terminal ballistic performance in ordnance gelatin during lab testing in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the .40 S&W earned status as "the ideal cartridge for personal defense and law enforcement".
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Ballistically the .40 S&W is almost identical to the .38-40 Winchester introduced in 1874, as they share the same bullet diameter and bullet weight, and have similar muzzle velocities.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The energy of the .40 S&W exceeds standard-pressure .45 ACP loadings, generating between 350 foot-pounds (470 J) and 500 foot-pounds (680 J) of energy, depending on bullet weight.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Both the .40 S&W and the 9mm Parabellum operate at a 35,000 pounds per square inch (240 MPa) SAAMI maximum, compared to a 21,000 pounds per square inch (140 MPa) maximum for .45 ACP.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] .40 S&W pistols with standard (not extended) double-stack magazines can hold as many as 16 cartridges.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] While not displacing the 9mm Parabellum, the .40 S&W is commonly used in law enforcement applications in keeping with its origin with the FBI.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Select U.S. special operations units have available the .40 S&W and .45 ACP for their pistols.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The United States Coast Guard, having dual duties as maritime law enforcement and military deployments, has adopted the SIG Sauer P229R DAK in .40 S&W as their standard sidearm.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] However, as of 2020, the Coast Guard has adopted the Glock 19 GEN5 MOS as its new sidearm.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Numerous federal and local law enforcement agencies are currently in the process of transitioning from .40 S&W to 9mm, most notably the FBI, who adopted 9mm firearms in 2015.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Customs and Border Protection adopted 9mm Glock handguns, replacing the .40 S&W Heckler & Koch P2000 CBP was previously using.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was originally loaded at subsonic velocity (984.25 ft/s (300.00 m/s)) with a 180 grains (11.7 g) bullet.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Since its introduction, various loads have been created, with the majority being either 155, 165 or 180 gr (10.0, 10.7 or 11.7 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] However, there are some bullets with weights as light as 135 gr (8.7 g) and as heavy as 200 gr (13.0 g).
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Cor-Bon and Winchester both offer a 135 gr (8.7 g) JHP and Cor-Bon also offers a 140 gr (9.1 g) Barnes XPB hollow-point.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has been noted in a number of cartridge case failures involving older Glock pistols, due to the relatively large area of unsupported case head in those barrels, given its allowed chamber pressure level.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] The feed ramp on the Glock .40 S&W pistols is larger than on other Glocks, which leaves the rear bottom of the case unsupported, and it is in this unsupported area that the cases fail.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Most, but not all, of the failures have occurred with reloaded or remanufactured ammunition.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] Cartridges loaded at or above the SAAMI pressure, or slightly oversized cases which fire slightly out of battery are often considered to be the cause of these failures, which are commonly referred to as "kaBooms" or "kB!" for short.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] While these case failures do not often injure the person holding the pistol, the venting of high-pressure gas tends to eject the magazine out of the magazine well in a spectacular fashion, and usually destroys the pistol.
[src:2012-aurora-theater-shooting/40-s-w] In some cases, the barrel will also fail, blowing the top of the chamber off.
